        introduction: "Bayeux is one of the rare Norman towns spared from the 1944 bombings — it was the first French town liberated by the Allies on 7 June 1944, the day after D-Day. Its intact medieval centre, with half-timbered houses and limestone townhouses, is exceptionally beautiful. The Bayeux Tapestry, a 70-metre-long embroidery dating from the 11th century, tells the story of William the Conqueror's conquest of England in 1066 — it is one of Europe's most precious artistic treasures, inscribed on UNESCO's Memory of the World Register. The Notre-Dame Cathedral, a masterpiece of Norman Romanesque and Gothic art, dominates the town with its twin towers. Bayeux is also the ideal starting point for D-Day beach visits: Omaha Beach is 15 km away, Gold Beach 10 km, the American Cemetery at Colleville-sur-Mer 20 km. The Memorial Museum of the Battle of Normandy chronicles the fighting of summer 1944. Taxis from Caen are widely used by international tourists arriving by train or plane who wish to explore D-Day sites using Bayeux as their base.",
