        introduction: "Mont-Saint-Michel is one of the most iconic sites in France and the entire world. A UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1979, this 92-metre granite rock crowned by its thousand-year-old abbey rises majestically from an immense bay that experiences continental Europe's greatest tides — up to 15 metres of tidal range during equinox spring tides. The Benedictine abbey, founded in 708 by Bishop Aubert of Avranches after a vision of the Archangel Michael, is a masterpiece of medieval architecture: the Romanesque cloister suspended in the void, the Gothic Merveille (13th century) with its stacked halls, the Knights' Hall and the light-filled refectory are breathtakingly beautiful. The medieval village winding around the rock, with its Grande Rue lined with shops and restaurants, its ramparts and the Saint-Aubert chapel, attracts over 2.5 million visitors annually. Since 2014, a 1 km footbridge replaced the old causeway, allowing the sea to surround the Mont during spring tides — a spectacular sight. A taxi from Caen is the most comfortable way to reach the Mont, which has no direct rail connection.",
